::: {#box-1 .callout-note .freshwater title="Box 1. Inland wetland ecosystem threat status across primary catchments" collapse="true"}
South Africa supports 22 primary catchments which are further grouped into six Water Management Areas (WMA). These are the Vaal-Orange, Pongola-Umzimkhulu, Mzimvubu-Tsitsikamma, Limpopo-Olifants, Breede-Olifants, and Inkomati-Usuthu. Each WMA is managed by an established or in process Catchment Management Agency responsible for overseeing the allocation, protection, and conservation of water resources in the catchment.

To support the consideration of biodiversity into emerging Catchment Management Strategies and implementation plans, the inland wetland ecosystem threat status headline indicator is presented according to the 22 primary catchments and associated Water Management Area.

Table 1.1. Ecosystem threat status of inland wetlands according to primary catchment and Water Management Area.
:::

::: {#box-2 .callout-note .freshwater title="Box 2. Inland wetland ecosystem threat status across the Provinces" collapse="true"}
The national status of inland wetland ecosystems is summarised according to each of the nine provinces and can serve as foundational information to support provinces as they prepare their state of environment reports and other freshwater biodiversity planning initiatives.

Table 2.1. Percentage of the total wetland area in each province that falls with each IUCN RLE category. In parentheses is the number of wetland ecosystem types per category per province (note these do not sum to a national number of threatened ecosystems as ecosystem types cross provincial boundaries). ![](imgs/ETS_wet_province_tbl.png)

The current data reflects ongoing collaborative mapping and data-sharing efforts between national and provincial agencies.

